===Etymology===
From {{af|en|snow|storm}}. Compare {{cog|stq|Sneestoarm}}, {{cog|fy|sniestoarm}}, {{cog|de|Schneesturm}}, {{cog|nl|sneeuwstorm}}, {{cog|sv|snöstorm}}, {{cog|is|snjóstormur}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈsnəʊstɔːm/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-snowstorm.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Bad [[weather]] involving blowing [[wind]]s and [[snow]], or blowing winds and heavy [[snowfall]] amount.
# A [[snow globe]].
#* '''1947''', {{w|Dornford Yates}}, ''The Berry Scene'', Ward, Lock & Co., {{gbooks|wWYIAQAAIAAJ|273|snowstorm}}:
#*: As we made our way down, my eye was caught by a '''snowstorm'''—one of those little glass balls, with a baby cottage inside.

